There are n tasks for you. Task i has an integer value of ci and a difficulty of pi. Also, you have an initial stamina of 1, which is denoted as S. You should process the tasks from task 1 to task n. For each task, you have two choices.

Give up the task. This way, nothing will happen. Complete the task. This way, you will gain S⋅ci points. However, S will drop to S⋅(1−pi100) after the task is completed.You need to maximize your points after you finish the process.

Input:
Each test contains multiple test cases. The first line contains the number of test cases t (1≤t≤103). The description of the test cases follows.

The first line of each test cases contain an integer n (1≤n≤105) denoting the number of tasks.

The following n lines contain two integers each, denoting ci (1≤ci≤100) and pi (0≤pi≤100).

It is guaranteed that the sum of n over all test cases does not exceed 105.

Output:
For each test case, output a single real number — the maximum possible points you can get. Your answer is considered correct if its absolute or relative error does not exceed 10−6.

Formally, let your answer be a, and the jury's answer be b. Your answer is accepted if and only if |a−b|max(1,|b|)≤10−6.

Strategy:
This is probably the first DP problem I have ever solved in a contest. I saw it is a DP immediately since it looks like normal arrays but the changing stamina makes it dynamic. Therefore I just needed to find what and how do I track to find the solution. It turns out that the correct approach is to go from behind as if starting from that position with stamina 1 and check if the next (at i--) position will improve by doing the task (with stamina 1) or it is better to keep current tasks and skip it. This way all the tasks at the end get gradually more and more multiplied with their corresponding stamina and we can never go wrong (decrease the profit) since the equation is dp[i]=max(dp[i+1], values[i]+(1-stamina[i]/100)*dp[i+1]). This way we either do the task and multiply all the rest by the stamina that would be left (this compounds by multiplying again and again that's why it works) or we just don't do the task. We keep track of the max in the dp array and output that. This also works because we can never really run out of stamina or it go negative since the equation is S=S*(1-difficulty/100) so worst case scenario we go to 0 and all the other values after dp[i] get multiplied by 0.